Dear Parents, students, staff and community, we appreciate your patience during this process. Although the technology department is accustomed to fighting viruses, it's usually done on the computer.
The Technology staff prepared and distributed hundreds of devices to staff and students for remote learning. We set up secure remote access for business offices and administration that was needed to conduct business as normal. Modification of phone systems to ensure staff could effectively communicate with the public, other staff and students.

Now the challenge of supporting more than 3800 users and their parents, across three school districts, remotely begins.

Email addresses have been established for assistance with devices for both districts at:

DistanceLearning@lehsd.org

DistanceLearning@prsdnj.org

Stay healthy everyone

James Bond
Director of IT services
Pinelands Regional School District
Little Egg Elementary School District
Bass River Elementary

Time to put it all back

In June of 2018 we removed all technology from the Pinelands Regional High School and redistributed it between the Little Egg Harbor School District and storage.
It‚Äôs now time to put it all back.
Within the next 10 days, the IT Staff will be configuring and installing:
130 wireless access points
243 computers in classrooms and labs with in-class sound systems
51 printers
50 visual presenters
100 phones
And that's just the High School.

We will also be:
Inspecting and rerunning approximately 50 miles of cable
Unboxing and setting up 270 brand-new chromebooks
Assembling 9 new chromebook carts with those chromebooks
Mounting 60 TV‚Äôs and 32 projectors.
Cleaning up and repairing any damage in our current 63 chromebook carts
36 PC notebooks and 170 Macbooks.

Reassembling tech in the Junior High after construction is completed.

Pinelands‚Äô IT Staff is working hard to achieve this in addition to providing technical support for our four school districts that start their school year in 10 days.

NJCCIC Advisory

Twitter Password Exposure
TLP: WHITE
May 3, 2018

Today, Twitter announced that a glitch caused some user passwords to be stored in readable, cleartext on its internal computer system. According to Twitter, the issue has been resolved and there are no signs of unauthorized access or misuse of the information.

Recommendations:
The NJCCIC encourages all recipients with a Twitter account review the company's blog post for more information and immediately change their password and enable login verification. Additionally, we recommend reviewing Be Sure to Secure Your Twitter Account: The NJCCIC's Guide to Accessing Twitter's Security & Privacy Settings for guidance on securing your account.
Please do not hesitate to contact the NJCCIC at njccic@cyber.nj.gov with any questions. Also, for more background on our recent cybersecurity efforts please visit cyber.nj.gov.
text:
NJCCIC Advisory

Twitter Password Exposure
TLP: WHITE
May 3, 2018

Today, Twitter announced that a glitch caused some user passwords to be stored in readable, cleartext on its internal computer system. According to Twitter, the issue has been resolved and there are no signs of unauthorized access or misuse of the information.

Recommendations:
The NJCCIC encourages all recipients with a Twitter account review the company's blog post for more information and immediately change their password and enable login verification. Additionally, we recommend reviewing Be Sure to Secure Your Twitter Account: The NJCCIC's Guide to Accessing Twitter's Security & Privacy Settings for guidance on securing your account.
Please do not hesitate to contact the NJCCIC at njccic@cyber.nj.gov with any questions. Also, for more background on our recent cybersecurity efforts please visit cyber.nj.gov.
